title: Tech golfers finish third at competitive regional
text: Tech golfers finish third at competitive regional by ATU Athletic Communications The Courier Your Messenger For The River Valley 11:27 AM, Thursday, October 15 2015 | 114 views | 0 | 0 | | ST. JOSEPH, Mo. — The Arkansas Tech men’s golf team showed it has the chops to be right up there in the Central Region this season, finishing sixth out of 20 teams at the Holiday Inn Express Classic/Missouri Western Regional Invitational.The Wonder Boys combined to shoot a 303 in Tuesday’s final round, enough to hold on for a three-round total of 41-over 893 to edge out Great American Conference rival Henderson State by one stroke. Fellow GAC squad Southwestern Oklahoma finished two strokes better than Tech and in fifth place. Central Missouri used a 279 in Tuesday’s round to best runner-up Central Oklahoma by three strokes at 871.Freshman Bryce Burke led the charge for the Wonder Boys once again, finishing his tournament with a 4-over 75 Tuesday for a three-round total of 5-over 218. That put him in a tie for fifth place, just one shot out of fourth. Junior Austin Smith made it two Tech golfers in the top 10, matching Burke’s 75 Tuesday and finishing with a 6-over 219 to pull into a tie for ninth.Junior Julio Arguelles carded a 75 in the final round to finish in a tie for 42nd in the 100-player field, shooting a 16-over 229 over the two days. Sophomore D.J. Godoy was part of that group with a 229 after firing a 79 Tuesday. Senior Dylan Lovell shot 78 in the final round, finishing the event with a 19-over 232, good enough for a tie for 53rd.The Wonder Boys will take a week off before closing out the fall portion of their schedule by hosting their own tournament. The Payne Stewart Invitational will take place Oct. 26-27 in Branson, Missouri.Frandsen, Golden Suns earn titlesat GAC PreviewOKLAHOMA CITY — Freshman Anna Frandsen ran away with medalist honors and the Arkansas Tech women’s golf team topped Henderson State on the first hole of a playoff to win the team title as well Tuesday at the Great American Conference Preview.The Golden Suns shot a 293 in Tuesday’s final round at Lake Hefner Golf Club to finish with a 21-over 597 for the event. Henderson fired the low round of the event with a 289 Tuesday to force the playoff. Southwestern Oklahoma was third, three shots back of the tie at the top.Frandsen followed up her first-round 69 with a score of 70 Tuesday to record the first title of her young career with a 5-under 139. She shot the best round of each day at the event, and was eight strokes better than the next closest competitor by the end.All five Tech golfers finished in the top 24 of the 63-player field, with four in the top 13 and three in the top 10. Sophomore Avery Struck fired a 75 Tuesday to finish in a tie for sixth at 7-over 151. Junior Jessica Sachs cut seven strokes off her first-round score, carding a 1-over 73 in the final round for a 9-over 153 and a tie for ninth.Freshman Pia Nunbhakdi finished alone in 13th after shooting a 75 Tuesday for a two-round total of 10-over 154. Junior Caroline Fredensborg finished in a tie for 24th and was the fourth Golden Sun golfer to lower her score from the first round, knocking five strokes off with a 77 Tuesday, good enough for a 15-over 159.Tech takes a week off before heading out of the country for the Illinois-Springfield Island Getaway in Rio Grande, Puerto Rico Oct. 26-27
